<br>
Actually, I was accusing Bogga of being ignorant and biased.  I took your Saddam post to be sarcastic.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>However, if the shoe fits...<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Anyone is allowed to have strong anti US opinions, including citizens of the US, which I am.  To disallow this is to go against the right to free speech.  Free argument and speech is a wonderful right, you should appreciate it a bit more than you seem to.<br>
<br>
As far as Somalia.  The US did not achieve its stated objective of restoring stability to the region, capturing or stopping Aidid and had to pull out its troops.  It lost multiple highly trained soldiers to rampaging mobs.  This is a loss.  Kill ratio is not a mark of victory.  If it was, Vietnam would be a victory.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>We simply discovered that the only way to bring peace to the region was to wipe it from the face of the Earth, an action we were neither willing or obligated to undertake. The region is still as anarchic, violent, and corrupt today as it was 10 years ago, but there's no reason for more Americans to die there.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
No, we discovered that our military command was stupid and suffered from severe underestimation of enemy capability, as you seem to.  We discovered that high tech does not make us invincible.  We discovered that we were unwilling to commit the forces and resources required to bring true peace to the area (A decision I agree with).<br>
<br>
To be honest, I dont understand you.  You state multiple times that people should go out there and educate themselves but when someone presents an opinion negative to the US you resort to the &quot;don't talk bad about us you ignorant foriegner, you have no right to talk&quot; argument.  I just don't get this.  How can you hope to promote educated discussions on any topic when you tell someone they have no right to talk?<br>
<br>
I'm a US citizen, I pay my taxes, I vote.  I contribute to the success of this country.  I have as much right to state my mind as anyone else.  I love how you try to present anyone who disagrees with you as having anti US bias though, do you think this adds strength to your arguments?  Do you think it adds credibility?  At what point did I say I hated the US or thought it was evil?  At what point did I say it was &quot;unchecked US agression&quot;?  Do you really see the world this way?  Do you really believes that everyone who has a negative view of <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>some</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> US actions has an anti US bias?  I just don't get this.  <br>
<br>
Point of fact, I love this country, I've said that multiple times before, and I admire many of the wonderful things it has achieved.  This gives me much more than a right to state what I think is wrong with it, it gives me a duty to speak my mind and try to correct the issue.  To see you resort to &quot;you're a foriegner, you don't have a right to speak&quot; is mind boggling.<br>
<br>
Honestly, I just dont get how you can claim to want to see Americans educated about topics and then resort to this sort of argument. <p><!--EZCODE FONT START--><span style="font-size:xx-small;"><br>
