<br>
Serious post coming up, and nothing that follows this sentence is in any way meant as a personal attack.  Nothing.  <br>
<br>
I don't think that &quot;everyone&quot; who disagrees with me on any issue regarding the U.S. holds an anti-U.S. bias or is wrong.  I realize that I do come off that way, because I'm passionate about what I believe in, but one of the things that I love dearly about this country is that we can HAVE discussions like this in a free and unregulated manner in an open forum.    Despite my bristling and occasional jingoistic tendencies, everyone is entitled to their own opinion and I read all of them and consider each for its separate merits (except for Kreket's--his I mostly just skip over and giggle at, because I'm pretty sure he's deranged and just desperately wants some attention).  Remember, we could NOT have a discussion like this in Iraq...Saddam doesn't hold those who speak out against him in very high regard.  I firmly believe that America is the best country on Earth, for no other reason than the fact that it attracts the best and brightest citizens of all of the other disparate regions and brings them together in one place where the overriding rule is tolerance.  It's a rule that not enough Americans adhere to yet, but with every successive generation we get better; more diverse and more accepting.<br>
<br>
Is that why I think we should disarm Iraq?  No.  There are plenty of Saddam-wannabes clamoring for attention all over the world.  I think we should disarm Iraq, by force, because it's the only logical option that remains.  I belive, and admittedly this is nothing but a well-educated and objective opinion, that Blix will NEVER find evidence that is satisfactory, and even if he does, the anti-U.S. contingent of the U.N. will still bend over backwards to prevent war.  In a way, that's their job.  But realistically, there are times in human existence when armed conflict becomes necessary, no matter how many antiwar and anti-violence marches there are.  This is one of those times.  Hussein is far too adept at subterfuge and bait-and-switch to get caught now--he's been deceiving the U.N. for nigh-on 20 years.  <br>
<br>
I've jumped the fence on this issue a few times in the past six months, but the more information that comes out, the more I feel that an invasion is going to be inevitable.  I've spoken out in this very forum quite strongly against military action in Iraq, and trust me, I'm the most vocal Bush critic I know, but the bottom line is that Hussein is absolutely pushing this as far as he possibly can, and in the long run this whole affair has the potential to destroy the alliances built after WWII and drive a huge wedge between Europe and the U.S.  Nothing would please Hussein, bin-Laden, and the rest of their ilk more than to see the West reduced to the kind of petty, squabbling circus we've all watched for the past 6 weeks.  The U.N. is a mockery right now, and the spectacle perpetrated by France (and to a lesser extent, Germany) in the past month has been downright embarrassing.  The *only* function it has served has been to illustrate how incredibly non-functional the U.N. can be--and I'm not saying that because I think the organization should bow down and pander to the U.S., I'm saying it because it's an inarguable truth.  <br>
<br>
We went easy on Saddam 12 years ago.  He didn't learn, and in return for our mercy he's repaid us and the rest of the free world by funneling money into some of the most notorious terrorist groups in the world and grossly inflating his own personal wealth at the expense of his people.  Like it or not, he's become a symbol, and something symbolic needs to be done with him.  I was about half-serious when I talked about isolationism earlier; there's a pretty significant movement in this country to simply shut ourselves in and lock the doors in light of the events of the past two years.  Some of those events are our fault, and it's been said that we &quot;had them coming.&quot;  Pride goeth before the fall, and all that--you know the story.  That doesn't mean that we shouldn't move to defend ourselves and our perception of freedom, and you know as well as I that if someone who spewed the kind of rhetoric that Saddam spews was about to come to power in a country like China, somewhere in Europe, or (God forbid) the U.S., they'd be taken down before they ever even got near political office.  Saddam is a holdover...he's a loose end and a lesson learned.  The sooner he's dealt with the better, and if he doesn't have enough common sense and humility to accept the exile he's been offered, there really is no diplomatic solution.  The man cannot be reasoned with.<br>
<br>
Anyway, the bottom line is I'm tired of hearing uninformed, ignorant twits who don't like the fact that they're lazy and jockey a Burger King counter spewing angry spoonfed opinions.  I'm not saying you're one of those people, because I know you're not, but our country and the world is full of them.  Our government is not &quot;out to get&quot; anyone.  Bush may be stupid, but his advisory staff and his cabinet are top-notch.  They wouldn't press this strongly for something like this lightly, and ultimately I, as an American, have to put my faith in them to do what's right.  As far as overwhelmingly powerful superpowers go, America is pretty damn benevolent--but I resent the opinion that this whole thing is some immature crusade to discipline a petulant child.        <br>
<br>
There's more that I want to say, but I'm tired and I'm going to sleep.  I hope this didn't come off as insulting. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#102960><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub169.ezboard.com/bmtboards.showUserPublicProfile?gid=fogelxanedu>Fogel Xanedu</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Training Karnors</span><br>  Posts: 1160<br> <font color=#628CBC>(2/20/03 12:51:11 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub169.ezboard.com/fmtboardsfrm5.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=435.topic&index=106>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: guns</span><hr size=1> Good post. <br>
