</span><!--EZCODE FONT END--></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#102960><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title><A HREF="http://www.ezboard.com/promotions/csc.html" TARGET="_blank" ><IMG SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/image/cscicon.gif" WIDTH="20" HEIGHT="20" BORDER="0" align="absmiddle"></A> <A HREF=http://pub169.ezboard.com/bmtboards.showUserPublicProfile?gid=sunmina>Sunmina</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Looting Highpass</span><br>  Posts: 122<br> <font color=#628CBC>(2/20/03 4:18:12 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub169.ezboard.com/fmtboardsfrm5.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=435.topic&index=109>Reply</a>    <br>ezSupporter<br> </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: guns</span><hr size=1> Ayerish,<br>
I would like to state again, for the record, that I love this country.  There are so many good things about it that it amazes me.  I can list all the good things if you want, it would take a while but I could.  However, what's the point of that, you already know most if not all of them.  Besides, if they're good, there's no need to discuss them since there's nothing wrong with them.  Please take all of that in mind when you read the next few paragraphs.<br>
<br>
I believe that many of the problems in the middle east and the persian gulf (no, these are not the same region) were caused by outside influences.  I believe the US was a large part of these outside influences for both good and bad.  Whether it was part of the cold war and support of Israel or developing oil resources without regard for native culture, the US was heavily involved.  This is neither an accusation against the US nor a claim of innocence for the rest of the world.  I could list the various ways in which European countries have screwed up in the middle east but that is not the aim of this discussion.  <br>
<br>
I believe the US was acting in its own self interest in these actions.  Again, this is not an accusation of evil.  As the head of a nation it is your duty to act in the interest of your nation and its citizens.  All those people who say foriegn aid is a charity are, for the most part, very wrong.  The return on investment on foriegn aid is sizeable and well known in advance of giving it.  Saying we went in to rescue the Kuwaitis out of good will is wrong.  We went in because our interests were threatened.  Again, this is not an &quot;evil&quot; act, it's a very justifiable act by a leader looking out for his nation.  <br>
<br>
With all that said, I do think the US made and is making a very serious mistake in the persian gulf by adopting a policy that is more concerned with short term returns than long term success.  The primary example I suppose is Iraq.  We clearly used them as a buffer against the Iranian fundementalists who, at the time, seemed like a major threat to our oil supply.  Rather than looking long term after the war was over and strengthening those ties, we ignored them.  We failed to learn the lesson of WW1, we left a broken country in our wake and we wonder why they lashed out.  After WW2 we seemed to learn that lesson and rebuilt Japan and Germany pretty much from scratch.  This left us with two valuable allies.  With Iraq we did no such thing.<br>
<br>
Both after the Iraq / Iran war and after Desert Storm, we left the Iraqies to fester under sanctions and conditions that were biased to say the least.  We implemented no fly zones to protect the Kurds while we allowed the Turks to slaughter them wholesale.  We enforced crippling sanctions because of possible nuclear buildup but did nothing when Pakistan did the same thing and paid off Korea when they wanted to do the same.  We said nothing about European contracts for Iranian oil (A country known for sponsering terorrists) but tried to block off sale of Iraqi oil.  Keep in mind, in no way am I saying what Iraq did or does is right.  I am just saying we ignore the same behavior in other countries.<br>
<br>
Now comes the current crisis.  What do you think the US will really do in Iraq?  Do you honestly think we will go in, remove the current goverment and then spend the billions and billions of dollars and the thousands of lives required to really rebuild Iraq from the ground up?  Or do you think we'll bomb the crap out of them and then leave?  I find it difficult to believe that we would commit the resources for a Post WW2 Japan rebuilding.  I find it hard to conceive of our current president ready to accept the losses and authorize the funds to do this.  <br>
<br>
This type of conflict just doesnt work, and I thought we would have learned that by now.  Either we go and we kill every last single one of them, man woman and child (a viable solution but one which I hope no one advocates) or we defeat them, stick it out for the duration and make sure the newly rebuilt Iraq doesnt see us as an enemy.  I dont think our current president has the balls for the second option.  All he's doing is slapping a bandaid on top of a festering wound.  He's not curing the problem, he's just hiding it from sight so his citizens feel like something got accomplished.<br>
<br>
It bothers me that somewhere in Iraq children will be growing up with a hatred of the US.  It bothers me because one day one of those kids will grow up and get their hands on the controls of a plane or the detonator for a nuke.  How will they feel about us at that point?  Will they see us as America the liberator, the country who freed them from tyrany and poverty?  Or will they see as America the aggresor, the country that bombs them on a regular basis?  What we did to Japan or Germany was a thousand times worse than anything we have ever done to Iraq or any arab country, but you dont see them willing to die to kill us these days, do you?  Don't you wonder why that is?<br>
<br>
Sometimes you just have to use violence.  Sometimes war is necessary.  I have no issue with this.  But this, this is a show war, nothing more.  A video game played for CNN and approval ratings.  It's a mistake, and it'll cost us in the future.<br>
<br>
Sorry for writing an encylopedia here, just had a conversation about this with a few friends and it got me all riled up. <p><!--EZCODE FONT START--><span style="font-size:xx-small;"><br>
