<!--EZCODE IMAGE START--><img src="http://www.eqfaces.com/photos2/boglurk.jpg" style="border:0;"/><!--EZCODE IMAGE END--></div><!--EZCODE CENTER END--></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#102960><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub169.ezboard.com/bmtboards.showUserPublicProfile?gid=ayerishstormcaller>Ayerish Stormcaller</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Egging EW</span><br>  Posts: 321<br> <font color=#628CBC>(2/20/03 9:09:29 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub169.ezboard.com/fmtboardsfrm5.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=435.topic&index=115>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: guns</span><hr size=1> Sun,<br>
<br>
The points you brought up pretty much illustrate all of the reservations I have about this invasion.  With the exception of it being a &quot;show war&quot; for CNN, I agree with just about everything you said (and even THAT point, to a certain degree.  I think everything ends up being show business in the end; it's the devolution of our global culture).  <br>
<br>
I don't know what will happen after the conflict ends.  It's almost entirely dependent on how long our involvement lasts, and what help we get from the rest of the U.N.  I think if we can shut Hussein's elite guard down and capture key strategic points fast and (relatively) painlessly, that the odds of Iraq being rebuilt and receiving tons of aid are good.  On the other hand, the longer the situation drags out, the more resources we expend to maintain a 150,000-man force at full alert, the less money and compassion Iraq receives after all is said and done.  Is this right?  Hell no, but it's reality.  <br>
<br>
I fully agree though, with your points about short-term blindness versus long-term gain.  Hussein is a direct descendant of that approach to foreign policy in the early '80s.  Pretty much every military action we've been involved in in the past 20 years was launched to remove a regime that WE put into power, thinking it was the lesser of two evils at the time.  We're learning, and the rest of the world is learning with us, but the sad truth is that no one is more qualified to make those mistakes and decisions than we are.  No other superior military force in the modern era has ever had the compassion and concern for the countries it's defeated than we have (and by we I mean NATO overall, but let's face it, most of the time NATO goes as the U.S. goes, with good reason).  If another nation is willing to field the military force and show the same broad-mindedness that we do, I would LOVE to hand off the torch; I'd love to have the luxury of living in a country where no one cares what my government does and we can all sit around eating chocolate all day criticizing the superpowers and not worrying that when we get on the subway in the morning that someone might open a can of Ricin in the next car.  <br>
<br>
With all of that being said, what are the long-term repercussions for leaving him in power?  Does anyone know?  Even the most liberal anti-war pundits admit that, left to his own devices, Saddam would do as much damage to the West as possible.  He's an egomaniacal, murderous despot with a God complex, who has convinced himself and those closest to him that he's some kind of avenging Arabic divine being.  Sure, there are other leaders in other countries that preach the same type of rhetoric that he's preaching, and I have no doubt that sooner or later all of them will be dealt with, because sooner or later they will threaten our interests; it's what despotic conquerors do--a fatal flaw, if you will.  Just ask Milosevic.  Hussein is, for all intents and purposes, pursuing the exact same agenda that Hitler pursued, and that's not an exaggeration.  The only difference is that Hitler was white.  So I mean, what's the alternative?  Should we back off, and continue to let Saddam play hide-the-smallpox with Hans Blix and his gang of pacifistic keystone kops?  Do you honestly think that Hussein would ever step down, or ever stop developing weaponry?  He's already said that he views himself as the savior of the Arabic world and that he believes he'll lead them to wholesale victory over the Western world.  Does anyone really expect him to wake up tomorrow if we back off and decide to turn over a new, peaceful leaf?<br>
<br>
Of course not.  If Bush were to do a complete about face, and start concentrating on the multitudinous issues that we're dealing with domestically, it would only fuel Hussein's fire, and make him even more arrogant, insolent, and violent than before.  When Bush Sr. went easy on him, all he did was use it as a leverage point to consolidate his power and influence...there's little doubt that he'd do the same again, and I'd bet within 5 years we'd be dealing with Iraq as a nuclear power.  Remember, North Korea signed a no-nuke treaty after we'd tried various times to pursue diplomacy with them, and now we've got an utterly insane fascist threatening the world with nuclear armageddon if someone doesn't pay attention to him.<br>
<br>
So I guess I'm asking for alternate approaches, and opinions regarding what's going to happen if we DO back off.  Is France going to be ready to be a reliable watchdog?  Is the unified Germany going to be able to spur the fairly weak EU to keep a leash on the world's dictators?  Can they even field a force capable of winning decisive victories without relying on the U.S. to provide the bulk of the military deployment?  Is Iraq just going to go away if we plant inspectors in there and let them drive around from hospital to university to palace for the next 4 or 5 years, chasing Hussein's tail?  Does anyone REALLY think that Saddam isn't hiding weaponry, and won't use it the first opportunity he thinks he'd get away with it?  Better yet, does anyone really believe that he wouldn't sell such weaponry to the highest bidder, as long as they promised to use it against the Western infidels?  <br>
<br>
For my part, I think the answer to all of those questions is a rersounding 'NO.'  I'm always interested in hearing other opinions, though.        <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#102960><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title><A HREF="http://www.ezboard.com/promotions/csc.html" TARGET="_blank" ><IMG SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/image/cscicon3.gif" WIDTH="20" HEIGHT="20" BORDER="0" align="absmiddle"></A> <A HREF=http://pub169.ezboard.com/bmtboards.showUserPublicProfile?gid=qikkiq>Qikkiq</A>&nbsp; <IMG HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10 SRC="http://home.si.rr.com/digitalgraveyard/squid.gif" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Karanas' Farmer</span><br>  Posts: 99<br> <font color=#628CBC>(2/20/03 10:46:33 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub169.ezboard.com/fmtboardsfrm5.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=435.topic&index=116>Reply</a>    <br>ezSupporter<br> </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: guns</span><hr size=1> If we listen to the US, Saddam has been defying this, that and the other thing continuously since 1990.<br>
<br>
Why it is so important to get Saddam now?  That is the fundamental question.<br>
<br>
The answer is actually quite simple, and it has nothing to do with oil, weapons of mass destruction, terrorists, Al-Qaeda, Israel, Islam, NATO, Kurds or anything else like that.<br>
<br>
The answer is that the economy was in pretty good shape from 1990 until about 18 months ago.  Nobody needed to go bomb Saddam because there was money to be made in the stock market.  Buckets of money in fact.<br>
<br>
Now though, the economy's in a downturn.  Like Caesar before him, GWB has the task of getting his people motivated and happy... and that's hard to do when Joe Average has just been laid off, his 401(k) has lost half its value, and YOU just got to be president of the most powerful allegedly democratic society on earth by a thoroughly undemocratic process that reveals one of the dastardly flaws in that society.<br>
<br>
So what do you do?  You take Caesar's approach:  Bread and Circuses.  Give the masses some blood and gore to take their mind off the problems at home and they'll stop bitching.  Best of all, if you start a war, you create jobs (soldiers, and industrial jobs to support the war).  You get to inject money into the economy (military spending) without looking like a 3rd world reject printing money.  It doesn't matter whether Saddam is hinding photon torpedoes that he stole from the USS Enterprise... all that matters is that the US goes and kicks some foreigner's ass to take the American people's mind off kicking their own government's ass.  Iraq is a convenient target because their leader is kind of an ass and the country has a funny name and if Adam and Eve got kicked out of the Garden of Eden between the Tigris and Euphrates then by God, no beret wearing fat-boy with an attitude is going to rule there.  Frankly, Tuvalu would be just as good if more than 10% of the US population could find it on a map.  Frankly, I'd have more respect for the US if they'd just come out and say this to the UN:<br>
<br>
&quot;Yes, we're going to Iraq to kick ass and take names.  We're having social issues at home and a good little war sorts things out.  We recognize that it's no more important to boot Saddam now than it ever has been.  However, it's CONVENIENT to do it now, it's not a bad thing for ANYONE if he's gone and best of all, anyone who wants to can participate and maybe get some of the same benefits we get.&quot;<br>
<br>
At least it would be honest.<br>
<br>
*THAT* is why the US is so willing to go it alone.  *THAT* is why they're willing to pull every trick to make it look legitimate when they know full well that it's no more necessary now than it was a year ago, or 2 years ago, or 5 years ago.  It's no more necessary for Iraq than it is for North Korea, or Libya.  It's not about oil, the US has lots of oil and they can much more easily take over Canada if they need oil.  It *IS* necessary for the US government to control its own people though and that's what this is all really about.<br>
<br>
